<HEADLINE>
<P>
SEMINARY ENROLLMENT INCREASES 5.1% 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Religious News Service 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Enrollment in the 203 seminaries belonging to the Assn. of Theological Schools 
in the United States and Canada increased 5.1% at the beginning of the 1989-90 
school year, including gains by blacks, Latinos, Pacific/Asians and women. 
</P>
<P>
However, while total enrollment was up, the percentage of full-time students 
continued to drop, reflecting a trend characteristic of seminary attendance 
during the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
"The sharp increase this year may well reflect the success of school efforts to 
serve a broader constituency with a variety of graduate-level programs," Father 
William Baumgaertner, associate director of the association, said in releasing 
the report. 
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the opening fall 1989 enrollment in schools belonging 
to the Vandalia, Ohio-based association totaled 56,082 compared to 55,405 a 
year earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
